<subSubSection pageId="39" pageNumber="40" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="39.[151,1437,151,1328]" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,328,1015,1040]" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,1015,1040]" italics="true" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">Comments</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Luk &amp; Marshall" authorityYear="2014" box="[335,564,1016,1040]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Aptilotella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="39" pageNumber="40" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gemmula">
<emphasis box="[335,564,1016,1040]" italics="true" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">Aptilotella gemmula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Luk &amp; Marshall" authorityYear="2014" box="[618,728,1016,1040]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Aptilotella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="39" pageNumber="40" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ebenea">
<emphasis box="[618,728,1016,1040]" italics="true" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">A. ebenea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are easily confused, externally differing solely by the presence of orbital bristles in the latter. The distiphallus of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Luk &amp; Marshall" authorityYear="2014" box="[738,875,1052,1076]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Aptilotella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="39" pageNumber="40" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gemmula">
<emphasis box="[738,875,1052,1076]" italics="true" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">A. gemmula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, however, has a prominent club-shaped sclerite, paired internal sclerites, and membrane-bearing ventral flanking sclerites, all of which are absent in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Luk &amp; Marshall" authorityYear="2014" box="[1315,1429,1088,1112]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Aptilotella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="39" pageNumber="40" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ebenea">
<emphasis box="[1315,1429,1088,1112]" italics="true" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">A. ebenea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Additionally, each half of the female tergite 8 is much smaller and rounded compared to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Luk &amp; Marshall" authorityYear="2014" box="[1182,1294,1124,1148]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Aptilotella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="39" pageNumber="40" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ebenea">
<emphasis box="[1182,1294,1124,1148]" italics="true" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">A. ebenea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The highly apomorphic hypandrium of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Luk &amp; Marshall" authorityYear="2014" box="[464,598,1160,1184]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Aptilotella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="39" pageNumber="40" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gemmula">
<emphasis box="[464,598,1160,1184]" italics="true" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">A. gemmula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is unlike any other in the genus.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="39.[151,1437,151,1328]" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">
Collection data suggest that in the 
<typeStatus box="[600,648,1196,1220]" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">type</typeStatus>
locality, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Luk &amp; Marshall" authorityYear="2014" box="[756,893,1196,1220]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Aptilotella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="39" pageNumber="40" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gemmula">
<emphasis box="[756,893,1196,1220]" italics="true" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">A. gemmula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may be commoner than 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Luk &amp; Marshall" authorityYear="2014" box="[1182,1294,1196,1220]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Aptilotella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="39" pageNumber="40" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ebenea">
<emphasis box="[1182,1294,1196,1220]" italics="true" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">A. ebenea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, on average outnumbering the latter at least twofold. These species are also sympatric with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Luk &amp; Marshall" authorityYear="2014" box="[1038,1222,1232,1256]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Aptilotella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="39" pageNumber="40" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pichinchensis">
<emphasis box="[1038,1222,1232,1256]" italics="true" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">A. pichinchensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a distantly related species which differs by its larger size, the lack of iridescent colouration, hooked curved dorsal sclerites and welldeveloped tripartite ventral flanking sclerites.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
